, they present a road map to the varying scales, angles and methods of transnational analysis that shed light on American politics, empire, gender, and the operation of power in everyday life.Contributors: Brooke L. Blower, Boston University; Mark Philip Bradley, University of Chicago; Nick Cullather, Indiana University; Brian DeLay, University of California–Berkeley; Matthew Pratt Guterl, Brown University; Jesse Hoffnung-Garskof, University of Michigan–Ann Arbor; Fredrik Logevall, Cornell University; Mary A. Renda, Mount Holyoke College; Daniel T. Rodgers, Princeton University; Andrew J. Rotter, Colgate University; Brian Rouleau, Texas A&M University; Naoko Shibusawa, Brown University  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNational characteristics, American, in art. 0aNational characteristics, American, in literature. 0aTransnationalism. 4aArt History. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aBlower, Brooke L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlower, Brooke L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBradley, Mark Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradley, Mark Philip, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCullather, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeLay, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoffnung-Garskof, Jesse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLogevall, Fredrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPratt Guterl, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRenda, Mary A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRodgers, Daniel T., econtributor.4ctb4https: